<font color="#FF0000">ON THE WRONG SIDE...</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 27 20:21:55 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
What a evocative few moments, to read Ken Hruby's &quot;Notes&quot;. Jesu, Joy of Man's Desiring is stirring in my comfortable living room; in the jungle, it would have convinced me that the player was one to follow...<br><br>
I flew close air support mostly in Cambodia. I think there were several wars going on all at once, which is the source of much confusion for veterans, but even more for those who were not there. I never had a problem with the war I was in, but on a larger scale, we were definitely on the wrong side. The irony is that we got started on the wrong foot because of our CLOSE friends, the French. Only later did our motivation become so wrapped up in the domino theory.<br><br>
I would like to go back, but Indochina is not there any more. The war did horrific things, but its been over for some time. Unfortunately, the GI pocket money which flowed into the region during the war started a social transition that has done more damage, by far, than all the bullets and bombs ever could.
<p><code>-- rmoseley@aol.com  (Roger Moseley, A-37 Pilot) </code><p>


